  <h>chrononyms</h>
  <p>Chrononyms are <a href="?xx=nouns/names">names</a> identifying events and historical
    eras.</p>
  <p>Chrononyms always seem to be <a href="?xx=nouns/name_descriptions">name-descriptions</a> rather
    than <a href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> – <g>An Cogadh Mòr</g>
    <en>The Great War</en>, <g>Bliadhna Theàrlaich</g>
    <en>1745-6</en>, <g>Linn an Umha</g>
    <en>The Bronze Age</en>, <g>An Seachdamh Linn Deug</g>
    <en>The 17th Century</en>, <g>Na Seachdadan</g>
    <en>The (19)70s</en>.</p>
  <p>Note that (post-specified) chrononyms are not lenited in the genitive eg. <g>deireadh Cogadh a’
      Chamais</g>
    <en>the end of the Gulf War</en>, not <bad>deireadh Chogadh a’ Chamais</bad>. <xl id="mmm">
      <li>
        <gd>Bha e mion-eòlach air <m>eachdraidh Bliadhna a’ Phrionnsa</m> [...]</gd>
        <tr>He had a detailed knowledge of the history of the Jacobite Rebellion [...]</tr>
        <ref text="2">td. 36</ref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <gd>[...] seinnidh Art MacCarmaig “Beinn Lì” le Màiri Mhòr nan Òran, mar chuimhneachan air
            <m>buaidh Blàr a’ Chumhaing</m> [...]. </gd>
        <tr>[...] Arthur Cormack will sing “Ben Lee” by Mary MacPherson, in commemoration of the
          victory in the Battle of the Braes [...].</tr>
        <ref text="400-166">td. 149</ref>
      </li>
    </xl>
  </p>
